<paragraph blockId="142.[151,1437,153,287]" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">
Four species described here with somewhat unusual genitalic features should be investigated further when more specimens are available. These species have a boomerang shaped piece at the apex of the aedeagal sheath. They also have shortened apical membranous sections of the LL, and this plus the presence of elongate ‘sausage’ shaped lobes on the LL is strongly suggestive of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ballantyne Lambkin &amp; Fu" authorityYear="2013" box="[548,674,261,287]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Abscondita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[548,674,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Abscondita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, to which 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wittmer" authorityYear="1939" box="[792,927,261,287]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Pygoluciola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[792,927,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Pygoluciola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is clearly closely related.
</paragraph>
